There is a huge variation in trait score across different countries. Singapore has the lowest, China the second lowest, the US the fourth lowest(?), and the other countries have much bigger score differences.

Anniceris suggests that incentive types are inherited by their parents. “Genetics?” lol.

A girl suggests that “incentive types” are inherited, but then renounces her statement. She says, “This is only something detected while young. Later it may be very different.” Rofl. My reasoning was that people at my job in the factory were a volatile mix of three different incentive types, and I thought it would contribute to longevity.

My description of the optimal “Jamaica” scenario in China is a bit “populist,” wanting to raise and educate more children, and not necessarily focusing on their educational culture. Yu Hua puts it in concrete terms: Bring more people to China for better economics of scale. This results in rapid progress in the aggregate. Children will learn to cooperate because of the many positives from copying each other.

The “antisocial ideal” choice is to freeze children. ISIL’s potential exists in a population in which 50% or more have high science skills and high social skills. This is what China is facing as it talks about Atlantis,
